<br>
There is Sindarin, which is the Noble Tongue. This is one of the better documented elvish languages, though has even bigger gaps than Quenya does.<br>
<br>
There is Telerin, which is the lanuage of the Sea-Elves, and is sparesly documented, and really to big a bother to learn.<br>
<br>
Dorianthrin is the language of Luthien, but is argued to be just a branch of Sindarin. There are about 80 words total of this language. Yet again, not to common.<br>
<br>
Nandorin is the Green Elf tongue, but again, there is very little about it beyond the history available.<br>
<br>
Ilkorin is what Nandorin is believed to be derived from.<br>
<br>
Tolkien has a whole set of languages thought up for this Middle Earth of his. I wish the man had finished writing them before he died. Based on what I have studied of Quenya, he was a very good linguist and brilliant at creating a language. After studying all of his works, I've been thinking about going to college to become a linguist as well, though I know I would do better to just bite the 10 years and get a Computer Science degree.<br>
<br>
But, I'm sure most of you are going &quot;Okay, she's weird&quot; by now, so I'll leave it at that.<br>
<br>
<br>
-Xelena<br>
